# Machine-Learning-intro

Lucerne University of Applied Sciences and Arts

Faculty:                      Business
Master Degree Programm:       Master of Science in Applied Information and Data Science
Module:                       MPM02 Applied Machine Learning and Predictive Modeling
Lecturer:                     Dr. Matteo Tanadini, Dr. Luca Mazzola
Students:                     Konstantinos Lessis, Maurice Willen, Nico Wyss, Sothy Yogarajah
Class:                        FS 2020, 2. Semester
Date:                         10. June 2020

Structure of Folders

Folder code
group_work_classification.Rmd   RMarkdown-file for classification models
group_work_regression.Rmd       RMarkdown-file for regression models

Folder data
ibm.csv				was downloaded from https://github.com/IBM/telco-customer-churn-on-icp4d on 18. March 2020
bikes.csv			was downloaded from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/bike+sharing+dataset on 18. March 2020

Folder output
group_work_classification.html  output html-file with classification models
group_work_regression.html      output html-file with regression models

<style type="text/css">.pagedtable {
overflow: auto;
padding-left: 8px;
padding-right: 8px;
}
.pagedtable-wrapper {
border: 1px solid #ccc;
border-radius: 4px;
margin-bottom: 10px;
}
.pagedtable table {
width: 100%;
max-width: 100%;
margin: 0;
}
.pagedtable th {
padding: 0 5px 0 5px;
border: none;
border-bottom: 2px solid #dddddd;
min-width: 45px;
}
.pagedtable-empty th {
display: none;
}
.pagedtable td {
padding: 0 4px 0 4px;
}
.pagedtable .even {
background-color: rgba(140, 140, 140, 0.1);
}
.pagedtable-padding-col {
display: none;
}
.pagedtable a {
-webkit-touch-callout: none;
-webkit-user-select: none;
-khtml-user-select: none;
-moz-user-select: none;
-ms-user-select: none;
user-select: none;
}
.pagedtable-index-nav {
cursor: pointer;
padding: 0 5px 0 5px;
float: right;
border: 0;
}
.pagedtable-index-nav-disabled {
cursor: default;
text-decoration: none;
color: #999;
}
a.pagedtable-index-nav-disabled:hover {
text-decoration: none;
color: #999;
}
.pagedtable-indexes {
cursor: pointer;
float: right;
border: 0;
}
.pagedtable-index-current {
cursor: default;
text-decoration: none;
font-weight: bold;
color: #333;
border: 0;
}
a.pagedtable-index-current:hover {
text-decoration: none;
font-weight: bold;
color: #333;
}
.pagedtable-index {
width: 30px;
display: inline-block;
text-align: center;
border: 0;
}
.pagedtable-index-separator-left {
display: inline-block;
color: #333;
font-size: 9px;
padding: 0 0 0 0;
cursor: default;
}
.pagedtable-index-separator-right {
display: inline-block;
color: #333;
font-size: 9px;
padding: 0 4px 0 0;
cursor: default;
}
.pagedtable-footer {
padding-top: 4px;
padding-bottom: 5px;
}
.pagedtable-not-empty .pagedtable-footer {
border-top: 2px solid #dddddd;
}
.pagedtable-info {
overflow: hidden;
color: #999;
white-space: nowrap;
text-overflow: ellipsis;
}
.pagedtable-header-name {
overflow: hidden;
text-overflow: ellipsis;
}
.pagedtable-header-type {
color: #999;
font-weight: 400;
}
.pagedtable-na-cell {
font-style: italic;
opacity: 0.3;
}
</style>

<style type="text/css">

.tocify {
width: 20%;
max-height: 90%;
overflow: auto;
margin-left: 2%;
position: fixed;
border: 1px solid #ccc;
border-radius: 6px;
}

.tocify ul, .tocify li {
list-style: none;
margin: 0;
padding: 0;
border: none;
line-height: 30px;
}

.tocify-header {
text-indent: 10px;
}

.tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 20px;
display: none;
}

.tocify-subheader li {
font-size: 12px;
}

.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 30px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 40px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 50px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 60px;
}

.tocify .tocify-item > a, .tocify .nav-list .nav-header {
margin: 0px;
}

.tocify .tocify-item a, .tocify .list-group-item {
padding: 5px;
}
.tocify .nav-pills > li {
float: none;
}


</style>

<script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };


    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>
<script>
window.initializeCodeFolding = function(show) {

  // handlers for show-all and hide all
  $("#rmd-show-all-code").click(function() {
    $('div.r-code-collapse').each(function() {
      $(this).collapse('show');
    });
  });
  $("#rmd-hide-all-code").click(function() {
    $('div.r-code-collapse').each(function() {
      $(this).collapse('hide');
    });
  });

  // index for unique code element ids
  var currentIndex = 1;

  // select all R code blocks
  var rCodeBlocks = $('pre.r, pre.python, pre.bash, pre.sql, pre.cpp, pre.stan, pre.julia');
  rCodeBlocks.each(function() {

    // create a collapsable div to wrap the code in
    var div = $('<div class="collapse r-code-collapse"></div>');
    if (show || $(this)[0].classList.contains('fold-show'))
      div.addClass('in');
    var id = 'rcode-643E0F36' + currentIndex++;
    div.attr('id', id);
    $(this).before(div);
    $(this).detach().appendTo(div);

    // add a show code button right above
    var showCodeText = $('<span>' + (show ? 'Hide' : 'Code') + '</span>');
    var showCodeButton = $('<button type="button" class="btn btn-default btn-xs code-folding-btn pull-right"></button>');
    showCodeButton.append(showCodeText);
    showCodeButton
        .attr('data-toggle', 'collapse')
        .attr('data-target', '#' + id)
        .attr('aria-expanded', show)
        .attr('aria-controls', id);

    var buttonRow = $('<div class="row"></div>');
    var buttonCol = $('<div class="col-md-12"></div>');

    buttonCol.append(showCodeButton);
    buttonRow.append(buttonCol);

    div.before(buttonRow);

    // update state of button on show/hide
    div.on('hidden.bs.collapse', function () {
      showCodeText.text('Code');
    });
    div.on('show.bs.collapse', function () {
      showCodeText.text('Hide');
    });
  });

}
</script>
<script>
window.initializeSourceEmbed = function(filename) {
  $("#rmd-download-source").click(function() {
    var src = $("#rmd-source-code").html();
    var a = document.createElement('a');
    a.href = "data:text/x-r-markdown;base64," + src;
    a.download = filename;
    document.body.appendChild(a);
    a.click();
    document.body.removeChild(a);
  });
};

<div id="initial-situation" class="section level1">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">1</span> Initial Situation</h1>
<p>Due to the size of the project we decided to create two documents:</p>
<ul>
<li>group_work_classification, IBM telco data set</li>
<li>group_work_regression, bike sharing data set</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<p><strong>Classification models with the IBM telco data set</strong></p>
<p>Part of this document are the classification models. We decided to use the IBM telco customer churn analysis data set from Github for for this purpose.</p>
<p>Data Source: <a href="https://github.com/IBM/telco-customer-churn-on-icp4d" class="uri">https://github.com/IBM/telco-customer-churn-on-icp4d</a></p>
<p>We are using EDA to find the most promising predictors and later on use them for our predictive modelling techniques to determine if customers are most likely to churn.</p>
<p>Target variable: churn</p>
<p>the customer churn column tells us if the customer has left within the last month.</p>
<p>Models in use and comparison: * Support Vector Machine * Random Forest * Logistic Regression * Artificial Neural Networks</p>
</div>

<pre class="r"><code># vector with the name of nominal variables to plot

df_ibm %&gt;% 
  select(churn, one_of(vec_variable)) %&gt;% 
  select_if(is.character) %&gt;% 
  pivot_longer(names_to  = &quot;VARIABLES&quot;,
               values_to = &quot;VALUES&quot;,
               cols      =  one_of(vec_variable)) %&gt;% 
  count(churn, VARIABLES, VALUES) %&gt;%

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1), legend.position = &quot;top&quot;) +
  facet_wrap(~ VARIABLES, ncol = 4, scales = &quot;free&quot;) +
  scale_color_tableau() +
  scale_fill_tableau() +
  scale_x_discrete() +
  geom_label(aes(x = VALUES, y = n, label = n),
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5),

<div id="modelling" class="section level1">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">5</span> Modelling</h1>
<p>In the following chapter we will apply the classification models from the lecture. In order to do so following steps have to be taken beforehand: * Splitting the data into train and validation set * Omit Unique Values (Customer ID) * Drop NAs * log transformation * Creating dummy variables * center &amp; scale data &gt; normalize</p>
<div id="split-data-into-train-test" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.1</span> Split data into train &amp; test</h2>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-text-begin -->
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li>The data frame includes unsuitable variables for the classification modeling</li>
<li>After exclusion of those variables, a first 80/20 split is made</li>
<li>Now the data frame df_01_training includes 80% of the original ibm data frame</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div id="data-preparation-preproccessing" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.2</span> Data Preparation &amp; Preproccessing</h2>
<p>Instead of using the Data Preparation &amp; Preproccessing steps that we have seen in the lectures we are using the tidymodels framework that allows us to create a recipe which we can reuse for different models.</p>
</div>
<div id="recipe" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.3</span> Recipe</h2>
<p>Create Recipe</p>
<ul>
<li>for the following classification models, we need to prepare our recipe</li>
<li>hence, we omit all NA Values (we saw, just around 3% of the data set is effected)</li>
<li>furthermore, continuous variables are being logarithmized for a better approximation of greater gaps</li>
<li>the dataset includes mostly categorical variables (Yes/No), the step dummy one-hot encodes these to ones and zeros</li>
<li>as we will see later, the models converge faster if the data is normalized and centered</li>
</ul>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->
<!-- rnb-text-begin -->
</div>
<div id="cross-validation" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.4</span> Cross-Validation</h2>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZGZfY3ZfdHJhaW5pbmcgPC0gZGZfMDFfdHJhaW5pbmcgJT4lIHZmb2xkX2N2KHYgPSA1KVxuZGZfY3ZfdHJhaW5pbmdbWzFdXVxuYGBgIn0= -->
<pre class="r"><code>df_cv_training &lt;- df_01_training %&gt;% vfold_cv(v = 5)
df_cv_training[[1]]</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-source-end -->
<!-- rnb-output-begin  -->
<pre><code>$`1`
&lt;Training/Validation/Total&gt;
&lt;4508/1127/5635&gt;

$`2`
&lt;Training/Validation/Total&gt;
&lt;4508/1127/5635&gt;

$`3`
&lt;Training/Validation/Total&gt;
&lt;4508/1127/5635&gt;

$`4`
&lt;Training/Validation/Total&gt;
&lt;4508/1127/5635&gt;

$`5`
&lt;Training/Validation/Total&gt;
&lt;4508/1127/5635&gt;</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-output-end -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuIyBleHRyYWN0IGFuYWx5c2lzIGFuZCBhc3Nlc3NlbWVudCBkYXRhc2V0XG5kZl9jdl90cmFpbmluZ191bm5lc3QgPC0gZGZfY3ZfdHJhaW5pbmcgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZShkZl9hbmFseXNpcyAgPSBtYXAoc3BsaXRzLCBhbmFseXNpcyksXG4gICAgICAgICBkZl9hc3Nlc21lbnQgPSBtYXAoc3BsaXRzLCBhc3Nlc3NtZW50KSlcbmBgYCJ9 -->
<pre class="r"><code># extract analysis and assessement dataset
df_cv_training_unnest &lt;- df_cv_training %&gt;%
  mutate(df_analysis  = map(splits, analysis),
         df_assesment = map(splits, assessment))</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-source-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->
<!-- rnb-text-begin -->
<ul>
<li>cross validation was achieved with a five-fold cross validation</li>
<li>for the following step, we change the split portions to its respective naming convention (training=analysis, assesment = testing)</li>
<li>create cross-validation datasets into analysis &amp; assessment datasets</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="model-training" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.5</span> Model Training</h2>
<p>The model is trained on the crossvalided dataset, in our case with the analysis-data for 5 times. For every split iteration 4/5 are used to create the model and 1/5 to assess the model performancel. This ensures that we do not miss any crucial part of the data in order to construct the model.</p>
</div>
<div id="measure-of-fit" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.6</span> Measure of fit</h2>
<p>As a measure of fit when evaluating the data we are using two metrics:</p>
<ul>
<li>Accuracy: As our goal is to predict a binary variable we use the accuracy metric. It shows the percentage of correctly classified instances out of all instances.</li>
</ul>
<p>Accuracy = <span class="math inline">\(\frac{Number of Correct Predictions}{Total Pedictions}\)</span></p>
<ul>
<li>Cohens Kappa: It measures the agreement between two raters and takes into account agreement occuring by chance.</li>
</ul>
<p>Cohens Kappa = <span class="math inline">\(\frac{p_{o}-p_{e}}{1-p_{e}}\)</span></p>
<p><span class="math inline">\(p_{o}\)</span> is the relative observed agreement among raters | <span class="math inline">\(p_{e}\)</span> is the hypothetical probability of chance agreement</p>
</div>
<div id="support-vector-machine" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.7</span> Support Vector Machine</h2>
<p>in the following chapter we train and evaluate support vector machine model the aim is to correctly classify the variable churn on the assessment data set</p>
<p>Classification SVM (radial)</p>
<div id="train-and-predict" class="section level3">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">5.7.1</span> Train and Predict</h3>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->
<pre class="r"><code># adjust model settings and engine parameters
model_svm &lt;- svm_rbf(mode = &quot;classification&quot;) %&gt;% 
  set_engine(&quot;kernlab&quot;)

svm_fit &lt;- df_cv_training_unnest %&gt;% 
  # preprocess dataset
  mutate(recipe       = map(df_analysis, ~ prep(obj_02_recipe, training = .x)),
         df_analysis  = map(recipe, juice),
         df_assesment = map2(recipe, df_assesment, ~ bake(.x, new_data = .y))) %&gt;%
  # fit model
  mutate(model_fit    = map(df_analysis, ~ fit(model_svm, churn ~ ., data = .x))) %&gt;%
  # predict
  mutate(model_pred   = map2(model_fit, df_assesment, ~ predict(.x, new_data = .y)))
</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-source-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->
<!-- rnb-text-begin -->
</div>
<div id="evaluation" class="section level3">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">5.7.2</span> Evaluation</h3>
<ul>
<li>in the following chapter we evaluate the performance of the support vector machine model</li>
<li>the aim is to correctly classify the variable churn on the assessment data set</li>
</ul>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->
<pre class="r"><code>df_svm &lt;- svm_fit %&gt;% select(id, df_assesment, model_pred) %&gt;% 
  mutate(df_compare = map2(df_assesment, 
                        model_pred, ~ tibble(churn = .x$churn,
                                             pred  = .y$.pred_class))) %&gt;% 
  select(id, df_compare) %&gt;% 
  unnest(df_compare) %&gt;% 
  group_by(id)

df_svm %&gt;% 
  group_by(id) %&gt;% 
  conf_mat(truth = churn, estimate = pred) %&gt;% 
  mutate(summary_tbl = map(conf_mat, summary)) %&gt;% 
  unnest(summary_tbl) %&gt;% 
  select(id, .metric, .estimate) %&gt;% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = id, values_from = .estimate)</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-source-end -->
<!-- rnb-frame-begin  -->
<div data-pagedtable="false">
<script data-pagedtable-source type="application/json">

<div id="random-forest" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.8</span> Random Forest</h2>
<ul>
<li>in the following chapter we train and evaluate the random forest model</li>
<li>the aim is to correctly classify the variable churn on the assessment data set</li>
</ul>
<div id="train-and-predict-1" class="section level3">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">5.8.1</span> Train and Predict</h3>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->
<pre class="r"><code>model_randomforest &lt;- rand_forest(mode  = &quot;classification&quot;,
                                  mtry  = 5,
                                  trees = 3) %&gt;% 
  set_engine(&quot;randomForest&quot;) %&gt;% 
  translate()

rf_fit &lt;- df_cv_training_unnest %&gt;% 
  # preprocess dataset
  mutate(recipe       = map(df_analysis, ~ prep(obj_02_recipe, training = .x)),
         df_analysis  = map(recipe, juice),
         df_assesment = map2(recipe, df_assesment, ~ bake(.x, new_data = .y))) %&gt;%
  # fit model
  mutate(model_fit    = map(df_analysis, ~ fit(model_randomforest, churn ~ ., data = .x))) %&gt;%
# predict
  mutate(model_pred   = map2(model_fit, df_assesment, ~ predict(.x, new_data = .y)))
</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-source-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->
<!-- rnb-text-begin -->
</div>
<div id="evaluation-1" class="section level3">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">5.8.2</span> Evaluation</h3>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->
<pre class="r"><code>df_rf &lt;- rf_fit %&gt;% select(id, df_assesment, model_pred) %&gt;% 
  mutate(df_compare = map2(df_assesment, model_pred, ~ tibble(churn = .x$churn,
                                                              pred  = .y$.pred_class))) %&gt;% 
  select(id, df_compare) %&gt;% 
  unnest(df_compare) %&gt;% 
  group_by(id)

df_rf %&gt;% 
  group_by(id) %&gt;% 
  conf_mat(truth = churn, estimate = pred) %&gt;% 
  mutate(summary_tbl = map(conf_mat, summary)) %&gt;% 
  unnest(summary_tbl) %&gt;% 
  select(id, .metric, .estimate) %&gt;% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = id, values_from = .estimate)</code></pre>

<div id="train-and-predict-3" class="section level3">

<!-- rnb-text-end -->

<pre class="r"><code>model_neural &lt;- mlp(mode = &quot;classification&quot;,
                    hidden_units = 3,
                    penalty = 0,
                    activation = &quot;linear&quot;,
                    epochs = 6) %&gt;%
  set_engine(&quot;keras&quot;)


neural_fit &lt;- df_cv_training_unnest %&gt;% 
  # preprocess dataset
  mutate(recipe       = map(df_analysis, ~ prep(obj_02_recipe, training = .x)),
         df_analysis  = map(recipe, juice),
         df_assesment = map2(recipe, df_assesment, ~ bake(.x, new_data = .y))) %&gt;%
  # fit model
  mutate(model_fit    = map(df_analysis, ~ fit(model_neural, churn ~ ., data = .x))) %&gt;%
# predict
  mutate(model_pred   = map2(model_fit, df_assesment, ~ predict(.x, new_data = .y)))</code></pre>

<pre class="r"><code>df_neural &lt;- neural_fit %&gt;% select(id, df_assesment, model_pred) %&gt;% 
  mutate(df_compare = map2(df_assesment, model_pred, ~ tibble(churn = .x$churn,
                                                              pred  = .y$.pred_class))) %&gt;% 
  select(id, df_compare) %&gt;% 
  unnest(df_compare) %&gt;% 
  group_by(id)

df_neural %&gt;% 
  group_by(id) %&gt;% 
  conf_mat(truth = churn, estimate = pred) %&gt;% 
  mutate(summary_tbl = map(conf_mat, summary)) %&gt;% 
  unnest(summary_tbl) %&gt;% 
  select(id, .metric, .estimate) %&gt;%

<div id="model-assessments" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.11</span> Model Assessments</h2>
<p>Taking a short recap we see how the models performed so far.</p>
<p>Wrong predictions made:</p>
<ul>
<li>~20% artificial neural networks</li>
<li>~20% logistic regression</li>
<li>~20% support vector machines</li>
<li>~23% random forest</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div id="model-comparison" class="section level2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.12</span> Model Comparison</h2>
<ul>
<li>with the short recap from above in mind, we would like to compare the outcome numerically</li>
<li>with the following lines of code, we fit again each of the above models and let them compete against each other</li>
<li>after the fit, the column <em>predict</em> is being extracted to later visualize for a better understanding</li>
<li>we evaluate the model performance with the testing dataset</li>
</ul>
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->
<pre class="r"><code>
recipe_classification &lt;- 
  recipe(churn ~ ., data = df_01_training) %&gt;% 
    step_naomit(all_predictors()) %&gt;% 
    step_log(total_charges) %&gt;% 
    step_log(monthly_charges) %&gt;% 
    step_dummy (all_nominal(),    -all_outcomes()) %&gt;%
    step_center(all_predictors(), -all_outcomes()) %&gt;%
    step_scale (all_predictors(), -all_outcomes()) %&gt;% 
  prep()

df_cl_train_pp &lt;- bake(recipe_classification, new_data = df_01_training)
df_cl_test_pp  &lt;- bake(recipe_classification, new_data = df_01_testing)


fit_svm &lt;- model_svm %&gt;% fit(churn ~ ., data = df_cl_train_pp)
fit_rf  &lt;- model_randomforest %&gt;% fit(churn ~ ., data = df_cl_train_pp)
fit_log &lt;- model_logistic %&gt;% fit(churn ~ ., data = df_cl_train_pp)
fit_nn  &lt;- model_neural %&gt;% fit(churn ~ ., data = df_cl_train_pp)


df_cl_predict &lt;- 
  df_cl_test_pp %&gt;% 
  mutate(&quot;SVM_&quot; = fit_svm %&gt;% predict(new_data = df_cl_test_pp) %&gt;% pull,
         &quot;RF__&quot; = fit_rf  %&gt;% predict(new_data = df_cl_test_pp) %&gt;% pull,
         &quot;LOG_&quot; = fit_log %&gt;% predict(new_data = df_cl_test_pp) %&gt;% pull,
         &quot;NNET&quot; = fit_nn  %&gt;% predict(new_data = df_cl_test_pp) %&gt;% pull)
</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-source-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->
<!-- rnb-text-begin -->
<!-- rnb-text-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->
<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->
<pre class="r"><code>df_eval &lt;-  df_cl_predict %&gt;% conf_mat(truth = churn, estimate = SVM_) %&gt;% summary %&gt;% mutate(model = &quot;SVM_&quot;)  %&gt;% 
  bind_rows(df_cl_predict %&gt;% conf_mat(truth = churn, estimate = RF__) %&gt;% summary %&gt;% mutate(model = &quot;RF__&quot;)) %&gt;% 
  bind_rows(df_cl_predict %&gt;% conf_mat(truth = churn, estimate = LOG_) %&gt;% summary %&gt;% mutate(model = &quot;LOG_&quot;)) %&gt;% 
  bind_rows(df_cl_predict %&gt;% conf_mat(truth = churn, estimate = NNET) %&gt;% summary %&gt;% mutate(model = &quot;NNET&quot;))

df_eval %&gt;% 
  select(-.estimator) %&gt;% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = model, values_from = .estimate)</code></pre>

<!-- rnb-frame-begin  -->

<pre class="r"><code>vec_metrics &lt;- c(&quot;accuracy&quot;, &quot;kap&quot;, &quot;precision&quot;, &quot;recall&quot;) # &quot;precision&quot;, &quot;recall&quot;

df_eval %&gt;% 
  filter(.metric %in% vec_metrics) %&gt;% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x = .metric, y = .estimate, col = model)) +
  facet_wrap(.metric ~ ., scales = &quot;free&quot;, ncol = 4) + 
  theme(strip.background = element_blank(), strip.text.x = element_blank()) +
  geom_label(aes(x = .metric, y = .estimate, label = model), nudge_x = 0.3, size = 2.5 ) +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(legend.position = &quot;None&quot;)</code></pre>
<!-- rnb-source-end -->
<!-- rnb-plot-begin eyJjb25kaXRpb25zIjpbXSwiaGVpZ2h0Ijo1LCJzaXplX2JlaGF2aW9yIjoxLCJ3aWR0aCI6N30= -->
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
<!-- rnb-plot-end -->
<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->
<!-- rnb-text-begin -->
<ul>
<li>As we can see, Log and SVM performed have the best results in terms of accuracy and kappa</li>
<li><p>Random Forest performed the worst; We expect the model to perform better with lesser pruning steps</p></li>
<li><p>one of the mostly used metrics is the accuracy score.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><span class="math display">\[Accuracy = \frac{\text{Number of correct predictions}}{\text{Total number of predictions made}}\]</span></p>
<ul>
<li>There are many cases in which classification accuracy is not a good indicator for the model performance. One of these scenarios is when the class distribution is imbalanced (one class is more frequent than others). This is actually the case in our data set. So we do have a higher amount of non churned customers. This being taken in account, the predictions get more accurate.</li>
</ul>
<p><span class="math display">\[Precision = \frac{\text{True Positive}}{\text{True Positive + False Positive}}\]</span></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="conclusion" class="section level1">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">6</span> Conclusion</h1>
<p>All models have performed not so well in predicting the customers who actually churned in comparison to those who did not churn (NON-Churners). In a next step it would be advisable to do feature engineering increase the prediction-accuracy of the churned customers. Another approach would be to retrain the models with balanced datasets. A possible way to do this would be to downsample NON-Churners before training the models.</p>
<p>All in all, there are only minor differences in the performance of the classification models. However the algorithms can be optimized by using hyperparameter-tuning and grid search.</p>
</div>
